title: Saying Goodbye to My Guide Dog & Flying to Tokyo! (first time leaving Elton behind - emotional)
description:
Guide Dog Care Instructions:

General care:
- Leave bedroom and sun room doors open at night so he can pick where to sleep 
- Clean his ears twice a week - use an ear cleaning sollution with one squirt in each ear, let him shake his head and then use clean, dry toilet paper to wipe out the inside of both ears - wipe til clean 
- If Elton is extra hyper, check his ears and bring him to the vet if they are looking red/infected - he displays hyper behavior when in pain ue to ear infections 
- He is not allowed on the furniture

Walks/Play:
- Walk him on the left side in a heal position, holding the leash close to the bottom 
- Elton needs 3 walks a day, do not let him sniff too much unless heâ€™s doing so to find a spot to pee or poop 
- On average, Elton poops twice a day but occationally itâ€™s just once. 
- Give Elton a toy from his toy bin when he needs extra stimulation and put it back in the bin so he doesnâ€™t get bored of it. You can let him choose the toy he wants by giving him a few options and heâ€™ll decide which one he wants to play with.
- If Elton seems really high energy, you may want to take him to the park before bed. Bring a large size ball for him to fetch 

Feeding:
- Please put the food in Eltonâ€™s bowl without him seeing you (close the door with him on the other side) when you open the door, ask him to sit and once heâ€™s sitting, you can give him his command to eat  
- Breakfast is 2 cups of kibble around 5:30am. If he wakes you early, tell him no and ask him to lay down 
- Dinner is 1 cup around 5:30 with 2-3 bumps of fish oil and one scoop of his skin vitamin 
- Bedtime snack is after his final walk, and is 1/2 a cup with a probiotic package 
- Do not give Elton human food of any kind

description:

22:55 - At this time I was posting my guide dog training videos that had been pre-filmed so I thankfully didnâ€™t have to film content for awhile and could just focus on my health.

title: How I Take A Selfie As A Blind Girl!
description: #Ad This new Google Pixel 7 feature that allows blind people to take a selfie is honestly incredible! I was so excited when I tried it for the first time, itâ€™s super easy to use and Iâ€™ve never tried anything like it before. I want to thank the Google team for thinking of something like this. So often accessibility is focused on allowing us as disabled people to do the necessary things in life, but like everyone, we also want to enjoy the simple things we just do â€œfor fun.â€ I mean, fun and joy is what makes life worth living! Being able to frame and take a selfie might seem silly to some but thatâ€™s probably because you can do it! Haha As a disabled person, every bit of independence counts, even if itâ€™s something trivial because independence isnâ€™t trivial. I really love this feature and I also think itâ€™s a great example of inclusive and universe design. While it may originally have been designed for blind users like me, I think so many could benefit from this and able-bodied people will benefit from it too in many situations! #GooglePixel #Pixel7 #Pixel7Pro #Selfie #HowTo #LearnHow #Blind #BlindGirl #Tech #Accessibility #InclusiveDesign

31:39 - 100% one of my favorites from this entire video! WILL.BUY.AGAIN.

description:

I was honestly really impressed with both the accommodating crew and the accessible design of the ship for me as a blind passenger. I miss it already and canâ€™t wait to go again! If youâ€™re in need of a getaway, book a Princess Cruise today:  https://bit.ly/mollyburke_PCL

Use code MOLLYBURKE16 for up to 16 FREE MEALS + 3 Surprise Gifts across 6 HelloFresh boxes plus free shipping at https://bit.ly/3IpjMyr!   
    
VIDEO SECTIONS:
15:50 - Research
18:08 - My Concerns

WRITTEN ON SCREEN:
9:45 - I had a lot of blind friends reach out during this journey and share similar struggles to mine, so I hope this helps
13:54 - IN EPISODE TWO I WILL SHARE THE OPTIONS!! Sorry - when 
filming it was intended to be all in the one video!
17:55 - The CNIB SmartLife team is SO kind and they just launched a new program to research more about smart appliances, so if this is something that interests you please look into joining!
22:28 - AND PART TWO!   

Learn about smart homes and disability: https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-assistive-smart-home-technology-for-disabled/

title: How Iâ€™ve Been Feeling About My Blindness Latelyâ€¦
description:
WRITTEN ON SCREEN:
4:55 - "My 24/7 visual hallucinations due to Charles Bonnet Syndrome that Iâ€™ve experienced since I was around 8 have also been bothering me more than they have in YEARSâ€¦ I donâ€™t know if Iâ€™m seeing an increased number of flashing lights and colors, or if Iâ€™m for some reason just more focused on them lately.â€ 
5:42 - â€œOne year in school one of my accommodations made was that I was allowed to go to school at 10:00am instead of 8:20am because my sleep issues were so bad and I was going for hospital sleep tests. I would get home schooled with the schools support for months on end most school years. I somehow managed to develop mystery lung infections, a severe vocal chord injuryâ€¦ you name it!â€ 
6:17 - â€œBefore anyones asks why weâ€™ve left it so long to properly deal with itâ€¦ honestly, when you have so many health issues always happening, itâ€™s easy to just leave things that seem less important to deal with later. Itâ€™s sad, because I know issues like this can be really serious and when they happen to someone with really good health, they deal with it right away but for me, Iâ€™ve dealt with so many health issues that some things I face just seem almost insignificant, despite the fact that theyâ€™re really important. Iâ€™m sure others who have dealt with many health complications can relate to prioritizing some health issues over others at times!â€ 
8:14 - â€œI also want to acknowledge that Iâ€™m aware how fortunate I am to be able to afford to work on my health in the ways that I do and to have had a family that prioritized my health and ensuring I get help over any other needs. Iâ€™m also lucky to have been born into a country with free healthcare and a dad who had a health coverage through his work. Many disabled and chronically ill people do not have the resources that I had growing up or have now and that does not escape me! I honestly donâ€™t know where Iâ€™d be today with my health if it wasnâ€™t for everything Iâ€™ve been able to do consistently over the years and continue to do now. When you deal with health issues, it can be incredibly expensive just to try and function and I wish more people had access to the care they need and deserve.â€  
21:15 - â€œI always fear new diagnosis or developing more issues. I have so many random little rare conditions, like Protein S Deficiency Disorder, that was only diagnosed by accident in my late teens and I fear thereâ€™s more unknowns and messed up genes living in my body just waiting to pop up at any momentâ€¦â€

description:
WRITTEN ON SCREEN:
0:47 -  â€œMy mom and I have our own table in a room and in the room next to it there are 3 large tables with 2 people at each long table, one at either end. We eat at the same time, just all spread out for social distancing.â€
4:22 - â€œThe mobility class will be in October but they did have a small group there for the Autism program!â€
6:57 - â€œTurns out itâ€™s a boy!"
8:08 - â€œIt was actually their family home that they chose to convert into a training facility! Incredible!â€
17:25 - â€œYouâ€™re also not supposed to hold anything in your right hand while working a new guide dog because you need that hand free to do visual commands through hand signals we use!â€

title: How I SWIM as a Blind Girl!
description:

WRITTEN ON SCREEN: 
0:47 - #realandrelatable 
1:43 - where I lived soccer and swimmer took place in the same season to as I progressed I had to pick one to continue doing at a competitive level 
7:08 - even with goggles on, the water can/will run into my eyes sometimes when I take them off because the rest of my face/hair is wet
7:54 - and when my head is under water I obviously canâ€™t hear them + if thereâ€™s lots of splashing sounds that echo at indoor pools it becomes difficult to locate exactly where someone might be
12:09 - this is what they did for swimmers at the school for the blind that I went toâ€¦ Iâ€™m sure they have better ways at the Paralympic level!
12:14 - 13:03: Time to get in, which is always the hardest part. Iâ€™m a baby about the cold water. Oh, thatâ€™s bright. Tummy is the hardest. Is it like that for anybody else? Just me? Iâ€™m lucky enough to have the pool to myself and when I have the pool to myself I sometimes just go off swimming in the middle, like, having fun doing hand stands and twists and Iâ€™ll kind of swim in the middle but when people are here, I definitely only swim on one side. Iâ€™ve gone to the side of the pool where thereâ€™s no stairs or ladders, because Iâ€™m trailing the edge of the wall so if Iâ€™m doing that with the ladder, I, like, hit the ladder. So, I go to the side with no ladder. Iâ€™m gonna dunk, put my goggles on and get swimming!
13:17 - 13:45: Hello. Oh hi! See? title: Beauty Products Made for Blind People?!
description:
#ad Thank you to Android for sponsoring this video. Learn more about Lookout by Google here: https://goo.gle/3oAu7Pr #GAAD 
FTC: This video is sponsored by Android. All opinions are my own! 

Shop the brands I mentioned and support their amazing efforts to be inclusive with their product design!
Victorialand Beauty: https://victorialandbeauty.com
Clean Logic: https://cleanlogic.com
Herbal Essence: https://herbalessences.com 
Humanrace: https://www.humanrace.com
Bioderma: https://www.bioderma.com
Lâ€™Occitane:  https://www.loccitane.com/

Watch my Allure video reviewing beauty products and their accessibility:  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u2Xx_C5X9lM&t=2s

Here are some of the articles I read to prep for this video:
https://www.voguebusiness.com/beauty/braille-beauty-packaging-loccitane
https://www.glossy.co/beauty/beauty-brands-are-improving-accessibility-for-visually-impaired-customers/

Stats and facts I shared:
- According to World Health Organisation, about 2.2 billion people live with some level of vision impairment, 36 million of whom are blind.
- 33 million Americans 18 and older are visually impaired and blind.
- 10% of 3.5 million have an income of $75K+
- Only a handful of beauty brands have invested in products and packaging that are accessible for the visually impaired (Vogue Business, July 2019).
- 55% of moderate or severely vision impaired people are women and girls (World Sight Day, 2019) 
- The total disposable incomes (post-tax) for working-age individuals with disabilities is nearly $500 billion. The total discretionary income is $200 billion.
- These billions of people want to buy person care or beauty products.
- Only 10% of the visually impaired community read Braille. Braille packaging can be technically challenging and costly to implement (CEW, February 2020; Vogue Business, July 2019).

- According to World Health Organisation, about 2.2 billion people live with some level of vision impairment, 36 million of whom are blind.
- 33 million Americans 18 and older are visually impaired and blind.
- 10% of 3.5 million have an income of $75K+
- Only a handful of beauty brands have invested in products and packaging that are accessible for the visually impaired (Vogue Business, July 2019).
- 55% of moderate or severely vision impaired people are women and girls (World Sight Day, 2019) 
- The total disposable incomes (post-tax) for working-age individuals with disabilities is nearly $500 billion. The total discretionary income is $200 billion.
- These billions of people want to buy person care or beauty products.
- Only 10% of the visually impaired community read Braille. Braille packaging can be technically challenging and costly to implement (CEW, February 2020; Vogue Business, July 2019).

Back with another fun shopping video today! I shopped at stores that I definitely thought were cool in middle school, but are they still cool? Let's see! 

Stores mentioned!

title: Gypsy's Tribute: Celebrating the Life of a Beloved Guide Dog
description:
My beautiful guide dog Gypsy sadly passed away after seven years of service on May 22nd 2014. Today, December 23rd, would be her 10th birthday. In honour of her, and the many things she accomplished, I am sharing this slideshow. These photos only show some of the amazing things she did and could not come close to capturing the incredible dog she was. Gypsy changed my life in too many ways to count. I can safely say I am who I am today because I had Gypsy by my side. She showed me how to love unconditionally, trust without fear, and to believe in myself when no one else did. Gypsy gave me the confidence and the independence I always dreamed of. Gypsy was stunning Labernese (Lab crossed with a Bernese Mountain Dog) trained by The Mira Foundation. http://mira.ca/en/
